*** Rationale
To handle a 20x traffic spike 100k logs per sec while staying well under the 800 dollars per month budget, we must eliminate expensive always on managed services like AWS Kinesis.
This design uses Vector as a sidecar to capture DNS logs  at the source.
By implementing a large disk backed buffer on the DNS hosts, we can absorb the 10 minute, 100,000 logs per sec spike locally without data loss or lagging.
The data is then streamed directly to AWS S3 in compressed Parquet batches.
This replaces high cost RAM based buffering with nearly free object storage, ensuring zero data loss at a fraction of the cost.

*** Prompt
Act as a DevOps Engineer. Your task is to configure a log collection system using Vector that handles a 5,000 to 100,000 logs per sec spike without data loss.

Collection:
Set up Vector to run on the DNS hosts to collect DNS requests, resolutions, and metadata.
Enable a disk buffer of 100GB.
This is critical: during a spike, Vector must save logs to the local hard drive instead of dropping them.

Storage:
Send the logs directly to an AWS S3 bucket.
Use the Parquet format and compress the data using ZSTD to minimize storage costs.
Batching: Wait until you have 10MB of logs or 30 seconds have passed before uploading to S3 to reduce request costs.

Safety:
Ensure at least once delivery so no logs are lost.
If the S3 upload fails, Vector should retry automatically using the disk buffer to ensure zero data loss.
